, led by General Atlantic and Stripes. Is this a good idea? Look, it=E2=80=
=99s a<i> giant </i>check written just three years after Vuori raised $400 =
million at a $4 billion valuation in a round led by Softbank. General Atlan=
tic and Stripes clearly concluded, after what was surely an intense due dil=
igence process, that pouring more money into the maker of unremarkable acti=
vewear in nice materials was sound. (Given the players involved and the lar=
ge cash infusion, there=E2=80=99s probably some downside protection mechani=
sm like a PIK preferred, but whatever=E2=80=A6 ) And while it might strike =
some as alarming that the company needs <i>nearly a billion dollars</i> of =
cash so quickly after raising <i>nearly half a billion</i>, Vuori will have=
 more than 100 stores by 2026, and that requires a lot of
capital. The plan must be to scale quickly and position the company for an =
I.P.O. <br/><br/>Is Vuori the next Lululemon (current market cap, $39 billi=
on)? Its chances are actually pretty good. Vuori represents the next phase =
of the activewear market, which is only in the early innings of formation. =
And while both Nike and Lululemon are performance-driven, and deeply rooted=
 in a sport=E2=80=94running, basketball, soccer, etcetera; and yoga, respec=
tively=E2=80=94Vuori, like its designs, is agnostic. This has made it appea=
ling to a wide range of people, especially work-from-home dads. =E2=80=9CIt=
=E2=80=99s just normal and unremarkable and kinda dumb in an L.A. way. Smoo=
th-brained running gear,=E2=80=9D says my friend <b>Chris</b> (not <b>Black=
</b>), who first started wearing Vuori two years ago, after discovering it =
at FrontRunners, Brentwood=E2=80=99s premier running store. =E2=80=9CI only=
 wear it in Los Angeles.=E2=80=9D (He=E2=80=99s based in Brooklyn.) <br/><b=
r/>I wonder, though, if that generic quality could limit its
long-term prospects. Nike and Lululemon have been so successful because the=
y have a <i>personality</i>. (Nike=E2=80=99s bland turn over the past coupl=
e of years is a big reason why it=E2=80=99s struggling right now.) People l=
ike specificity, and they want to believe that they=E2=80=99re buying somet=
hing that will make them <i>special</i>, no matter how many other people ow=
n that same thing. This is how Louis Vuitton sells $20 billion worth of pro=
ducts a year. So what is Vuori=E2=80=99s <i>thing </i>besides being <i>noth=
ing</i>?<br/><br/>Apparently, at least, there is an interest in being in th=
e <i>mix. </i>On Tuesday night in Los Angeles, the brand hosted a dinner at=
 the Chateau Marmont, attended by a smattering of athletes and insiders lik=
e <b>Karla Welch</b> <i>and</i> <b>Will</b> <b>Welch</b> (unrelated!), who=
=E2=80=99s in town for the <i>GQ</i> Men of the Year party. I found out bec=
ause I was <i>also</i> at the Chateau that night, in the parlor, attending =
a celeb-filled reading of <b>Lili</b>
<b>Anolik</b>=E2=80=99s <i>Didion and Babitz </i>book. (Anolik=E2=80=99s hu=
sband is a big-time celebrity dermatologist, which is one reason her book p=
arties on both coasts have been so successfully attended.) I assume there w=
as very little overlap in attendance, other than <b>Jason</b> <b>Stewart</b=
>. <b>Guram</b> <b>Gvasalia</b> was not headed to Vuori. Anyway, it=E2=80=
=99s up to Vuori founder and C.E.O. <b>Joe</b> <b>Kudla</b> to keep the mas=
ses interested, and convince everyone that this isn=E2=80=99t just another =
private equity brand.</li></ul></td>
