          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The LVMH succession=
 game is a long one. <b>Bernard Arnault</b>, the company=E2=80=99s mastermi=
nd and multidimensional architect, is a youngish 75 and isn=E2=80=99t going=
 <i>anywhere</i> anytime in the next decade. Meanwhile, three of his five c=
hildren are <i>under 35</i> (two are actually <i>under 30</i>). Who among h=
is offspring, from two marriages, is first in line to succeed him is a ques=
tion that likely won=E2=80=99t be answered for five or even 10 years. <br/>=
<br/>But this morning, a member of the next generation made a significant l=
eap, triggering executives to shift alliances and face the reality that, li=
ke it or not, the kids are ascending and gaining <i>real </i>power. <b>Alex=
andre</b> <b>Arnault</b>, the 32-year-old middle child and current head of =
communications and product at Tiffany, the luxury leader=E2=80=99s still-re=
cent acquisition, has been named deputy
C.E.O. of Mo=C3=ABt Hennessy, the conglomerate=E2=80=99s struggling wine an=
d spirits division. His supervisor will be current LVMH C.F.O. <b>Jean-Jacq=
ues Guiony</b>, who is replacing<b> Philippe Schaus</b> to oversee the grou=
p. They both start in February. Alexandre will be relocating to Paris from =
New York.<br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s no surprise that Schaus is out=E2=80=94the =
division, 30 percent of which is owned by beverage conglomerate Diageo, is =
down 8 percent in the first nine months of 2024. Additionally, LVMH has bee=
n somewhat ruthlessly removing underperforming executives over age 60 durin=
g this past year. The decision to have Guiony, a 62-year-old numbers guy wi=
th an impeccable reputation, oversee wine and spirits indicates a preferenc=
e for performance and practicality over flair. <br/><br/>More significantly=
, Bernard has chosen arguably his most trusted deputy to mentor his son. It=
=E2=80=99s a similar arrangement to how <b>Michael Burke</b> offered <b>Del=
phine Arnault </b>the Cardinal Richelieu
treatment at Louis Vuitton. And now <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e=
/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUTFBiVmR1c2VyckhlbHQ2UGNHRT0i=
LCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvZGVscGhpbmUtZGlvci10by1kb3MvP3V0bV9jYW1=
wYWlnbj1MaW5lK1NoZWV0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTElMkYxNDI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2=
NvbnRlbnQ9TGluZStTaGVldCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODEwJTJGMiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2d=
XRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2=
dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQ=
xMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoxMTE2NjkwfQ/a5339b25dfc6c8898da16c1c4cc0b7aafb259f06236=
1b8fe2dcb19c1e1587e2d" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-wei=
ght:bold" class=3D"sdf">Delphine is running Dior</a></u>, the second-most i=
mportant fashion brand in the group.<br/><br/>In his brief tenure at the fa=
mily business, Alexandre has already become <i>something </i>of a turnaroun=
d guy=E2=80=94first at Rimowa (where he reported in to Guiony), then Tiffan=
y. But Rimowa, which he identified as a prospect and helped the company acq=
uire, was a <i>fairly </i>easy fix: Since the manufacturing and supply chai=
ns were in place, he could focus mostly on the marketing, style upgrades, a=
nd, crucially, refining the distribution strategy. (You used to be able to =
buy Rimowa suitcases on sale at dinky luggage stores the world over. Now, n=
ot so much.) <br/><br/>Tiffany was harder, and Alexandre <u><a href=3D"http=
s://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUTFBiVmR=
1c2VyckhlbHQ2UGNHRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvYXJuYXVsdHMtd2FudC=
10aWZmYW55LXRvLWJlLW5ldy1jYXJ0aWVyLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249TGluZStTaGVldCstK1NVQ=
lNDUklCRVJTKyUyODExJTJGMTQyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PUxpbmUrU2hlZXQrLStT=
VUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMCUyRjIlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9=
uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0Mm=
FiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6ODc3NjI4f=
Q/e662e41d76028575e84ae6add5d8bb51ea08480075348a56237f4fad50367648" style=
=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">has =
been criticized</a></u> for his work there by both LVMH insiders and disgru=
ntled retail employees, alike, who feel that the dusty brand has lost much =
of its charm in the modernization process. Nevertheless, Tiffany is bigger =
and more profitable than it ever was before the acquisition. The flagship N=
ew York location was renovated, celebrities were enlisted for collaboration=
s, and pricing was adjusted (silver is nearly a fifth of annual sales, I he=
ar, and the most profitable). And while not everyone agrees with the aesthe=
tic direction (there are <i>other</i> interior designers in the universe be=
sides <b>Peter</b> <b>Marino</b>), people are shopping there again. <br/><b=
r/>Indeed, the Fifth Avenue flagship is one of the most=E2=80=94if not
<i>the</i> most=E2=80=94productive, single-brand stores in the world. While=
 revenue was expected to drop this year, I=E2=80=99ve heard from a number o=
f people that Tiffany may beat projections thanks to stronger-than-expected=
 sales since August. <br/></td>
